he asymmetries to look for in the MSA\n\nRead every operative clause looking specifically for these recurring patterns. Each is a routine push-back point.\n\n## 2.1 Indemnities\n\n- **One-sided indemnity** running only from supplier to buyer (or only buyer to supplier in a buyer-side deal) — push for mutual where appropriate.\n- **Uncapped indemnity** sitting outside the cap-of-liability clause — the most expensive class of risk; almost always negotiable to a separate higher cap.\n- **Indemnity scope drift** — covering breach of contract, negligence, defect, IP, and \"any applicable law\" in one sweep. Decompose into named heads of liability.\n\n## 2.2 Liability caps and exclusions\n\n- **Asymmetric caps** — supplier capped at 12 months' fees while buyer is capped at a fixed (often tiny) amount, or uncapped. The MSA should have symmetric default caps with named carve-outs.\n- **Carve-outs reading more like exclusions** — IP infringement, confidentiality, data protection, fraud, death/personal injury. Confirm the carve-outs are mutual.\n- **Pure economic loss / loss of profit exclusions** — fine in principle, but check the carve-outs from the exclusion don't reintroduce uncapped exposure via the back door.\n\n## 2.3 Termination\n\n- **Termination for convenience by buyer only** — without a corresponding right for the supplier, this turns a 3-year framework into a 30-day rolling arrangement. Either remove or reciprocate; if neither, secure protective compensation (wind-down costs, work-in-progress, stranded costs, demobilisation).\n- **Termination triggers that include \"change of control to a competitor\"** — push to define \"competitor\" tightly. Without definition this is buyer discretion.\n- **Termination for insolvency / change of control / material breach** — typically reciprocal in principle but check the cure periods are workable (30 days is standard).\n\n## 2.4 IP\n\n- **Foreground IP assignment to buyer** for any work product — heavily restrict scope. The bidder's tooling, methodologies, frameworks, and pre-existing know-how (Background IP) must be carved out. Joint Foreground IP arising from the work should usually be jointly owned or licensed back to the supplier, not assigned absolutely to the buyer.\n- **Perpetual royalty-free licence to background IP** \"embedded in\" deliverables — usually too broad. Limit to the scope necessary to use the deliverables for their intended purpose.\n\n## 2.5 Audit rights\n\n- Check the audit clause for scope (records only, or premises + systems + sub-contractors), notice period (5 BD is workable; 24h is not), frequency (twice a year is workable; \"at any time\" is not), cost (party-bearing rules), and survival period (4-6 years is reasonable; longer is not).\n\n## 2.6 Payment\n\n- **Payment terms longer than 60 days** are aggressive in most UK / EU markets. 90 days should be challenged unless reflected in pricing.\n- **Late-payment interest at the statutory minimum** — under the Late Payment of Commercial Debts (Interest) Act 1998 the statutory rate is 8% over the Bank of England base rate. Confirm this is what is intended; aggressive buyers sometimes drop the rate.\n- **Set-off rights** unilateral to the buyer — push for mutual or remove.\n\n## 2.7 Pricing protections\n\n- **Most-favoured-customer (MFC) clauses** — combined with audit rights they create a continuous compliance burden. Either resist or limit to genuinely comparable products on genuinely comparable terms within a defined customer cohort.\n- **Open-book costing** for nominated SKUs — confirm what \"open-book\" means in practice, who sees the data, and the consequences of margin compression.\n- **Unilateral price-adjustment rights by buyer** — should not exist. Pricing changes require mutual agreement.\n\n## 2.8 Governing law and jurisdiction\n\n- Check governing law matches the bidder's preferred forum. Local-buyer-jurisdiction is standard but problematic for cross-border bids.\n- Check the dispute-resolution path — courts vs. arbitration. Arbitration is usually preferable for cross-border deals; courts for domestic.\n\n# 3. Battle of forms\n\nWhen buyers issue an RFQ pack containing both an MSA and standalone T&Cs:\n\n- The **T&Cs almost always state they prevail over any other document.** That clause is often in the GTCs themselves and is the first place to look.\n- The MSA may contain a contradictory order-of-precedence clause (MSA prevails). Flag both clauses for the negotiation table.\n- Pricing schedules, SLAs, and annexes often carry their own clauses purporting to override the MSA. Map the precedence stack on a single page before negotiating.\n- The bidder's accepted position should normally be: **bid response wording > redlined MSA > buyer's GTCs**, with any annexes ranking below the MSA. If the buyer refuses to flip the precedence, the bidder is effectively bidding on the T&Cs alone — price accordingly.\n\n# 4. Procurement-specific risk areas\n\nThese show up in procurement-led bids more than in standalone deals:\n\n- **Audit rights extending to subsidiaries and sub-suppliers** — supplier may not be able to grant these. Limit to the supplier and named principal sub-suppliers.\n- **ESG attestation requirements** that demand a certifying signature at director level — confirm the bidder can attest accurately, particularly around Scope 3 emissions and SBTi targets. Negative attestations on disclosed non-compliance are usually safer than over-claiming.\n- **Data Processing Annex by reference** — never accept \"as updated by the controller from time to time\" wording. The DPA must be fixed at a known version with negotiated change procedure.\n- **Cyber-security minima** baked into the compliance annex (Cyber Essentials Plus, MFA, encryption, pen-testing, incident-notification windows) — these are often achievable but the timelines and audit rights need scoping.\n- **Strategic stock holding** — confirm the supplier is being compensated for stock-holding cost, including capit